Virtual Machines and Containers are both used to run applications in isolated environments, but they differ in architecture and performance.

Virtual Machines use separate operating systems for each instance, making them heavier and slower but providing strong isolation.

Containers, on the other hand, share the host operating system kernel, making them lightweight, faster, and more efficient.

Because of their speed, scalability, and portability, containers have become the foundation of modern DevOps, CI/CD, and cloud-native applications using technologies like Docker and Kubernetes.

In modern production environments, companies often use both VMs and Containers together to achieve scalability, flexibility, and efficient resource utilization.

